{"status": "success", "totalResults": 4021, "results": [{"article_id": "c0f99d716fb28b752c73a36b6ba921ca", "link": "http://thearabweekly.com/turkey-steps-canada-led-defence-bank-founding-member", "title": "Turkey steps into Canada-led defence bank as founding member", "description": "Turkey steps into Canada-led defence bank as founding member \u201cTurkey has informed Canada that it will participate in the bank,\u201d a Turkish official said. Monday 13/07/2026 Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan meets Canadian Prime Minister Mark Carney, on the sidelines of the NATO leaders Summit, at the Presidential Palace in Ankara, July 7, 2026. ANKARA Turkey has informed Canada that it will participate in the Defence Security and Resilience Bank as a founding member, a Turkish official said on Monday. Defence ministry sources said over the weekend that Turkey was still evaluating possible participation after Canadian Prime Minister Mark Carney said at a NATO summit in Ankara last week that nine countries, including Turkey, had committed to the bank, in what was seen as a boost for the multilateral drive to help rearm allied nations. \u201cTurkey has informed Canada that it will participate in the bank,\u201d the official said. According to Carney\u2019s statement last week, Albania, Belgium, Greece, Latvia, Luxembourg, Romania, Turkey and Ukraine had all pledged their support to the bank, which will be based in Canada. The roster contained no heavyweight G7 nations other than Canada, potentially limiting the bank\u2019s financial firepower, although Canada\u2019s foreign minister, Anita Anand, said it would remain open to new members. The bank\u2019s purpose is to bolster the defence of like-minded allied nations by raising up to \u00a3100 billion ($134 billion) in cheap financing.", "content": "ONLY AVAILABLE IN PAID PLANS", "keywords": null, "creator": null, "language": "english", "country": ["jordan", "saudi arabia", "libya", "iraq", "morocco", "algeria", "egypt", "tunis